On March 30, 2009, President Obama signed HR 146, the Omnibus Public Lands Management Act of 2009. The bill incorporates more than 150 individual bills and designates about 2 million acres of new wilderness areas. It also creates ten new National Heritage Areas and authorizes land exchanges, water projects, and various studies. The bill includes the Christopher and Dana Reeve Paralysis Act, which focuses on paralysis research, rehabilitation, and improving the quality of life for people with paralysis and physical disabilities. The signing ceremony will include remarks from President Obama and the presence of Interior Secretary Ken Salazar and 13 members of Congress. The audience will include representatives from conservation groups, sportsmen's organizations, the Navajo nation, disability advocates, and members of Congress.